The RPI LINAC produces a 60-MeV pulsed
electron beam. Neutrons are generated from electrons
using tantalum photoneutron targets. The beam
conditions during these experiments were 1-3 micros
wide pulses at 25 pulses per second for thermal
measurements producing an average beam current of
8-19 microA, and 120-160 ns wide pulses at 250 pulses
per second for epithermal measurements producing an
A variety of gadolinium samples were used in these
experiments. Two levels of enriched gadolinium oxide
powder were available. One contained 70% 157Gd and
isotopes. The best method for providing a thin,
uniform sample was to manufacture liquid samples in
quartz cells. Deuterated nitric acid was used to
dissolve the Gd2O3. It was then diluted with D2O to
produce the desired Gd concentrations. Nine different
dilutions of these mixtures were used.
